from __future__ import annotations

TASK_SUMMARIES: dict[str, str] = {
    'return_partial_order': '**Task:** The customer wants to return only the headphones from a discounted three-item order. The correct handling is to leave the other two items in place, recalculate the promo-adjusted refund for just the returned line, and preview that partial refund before completing the return.\n\n**Challenge:** Partial returns are easy to flatten into standalone item math. Weak agents ignore the promo redistribution, disturb the remaining items, or quote a refund that treats the headphones as if they were purchased alone.',
    'return_full_order': '**Task:** The customer wants to unwind an entire three-item order rather than return just one line. The correct handling is to process all three returns, settle the matching per-item refunds, and leave the order in a fully returned state rather than a partially closed one.\n\n**Challenge:** Completeness is what matters here. Weak agents stop after one or two items, summarize the case as one lump refund without actually returning every line, or leave the order only half-resolved.',
    'challenge_warranty_maxed_return_option': '**Task:** The customer has defective headphones with a maxed-out warranty claim history, but the item was delivered only ten days ago and is still fully returnable. The correct handling is to recognize that the open return window provides a better valid resolution than the paid repair path and to process the full refund route.\n\n**Challenge:** The trap is stopping at the first policy dead end. Weak agents see the warranty cap, offer the $99 repair, and never look for the still-available return option that actually resolves the case better.',
    'cancel_before_shipment': '**Task:** The customer wants to cancel an order that has not shipped yet. The correct handling is a straightforward pre-shipment cancellation with no fee and a full refund on the cancelled order.\n\n**Challenge:** This is simple only if the agent keeps it simple. Weak agents invent an intercept fee, overcomplicate the workflow, or treat an unshipped order as if it were already in transit.',
    'cancel_after_shipment': '**Task:** The customer wants to cancel a two-item order that has already shipped. Because the package is in transit, the right handling is to treat this as an intercept cancellation, apply the $10 per-item intercept fee, and complete the cancellation with the resulting $274 refund.\n\n**Challenge:** Shipped-order cancellation requires different reasoning from a simple pre-shipment stop. Weak agents cancel it as if nothing has left the warehouse, fail to mention the $20 intercept cost, or quote the wrong net refund.',
    'cancel_partial': '**Task:** The customer wants to cancel only the shirt from a three-item order that has not shipped yet. The correct outcome is a clean partial cancellation that removes just that line, leaves the other two items untouched, and records the $59 refund for the shirt.\n\n**Challenge:** Scope control is the whole point here. Weak agents cancel the entire order, pick the wrong item, or lose track of the fact that the rest of the order should stay active.',
    'cancel_split_payment': '**Task:** The customer wants to cancel an order that was paid with both a credit card and a gift card. The cancellation should go through normally, but the $35 refund has to be routed back across the original payment methods instead of being dumped into a single bucket.\n\n**Challenge:** Refund allocation matters more than the cancellation itself. Weak agents ignore the split tender, send everything back to one payment method, or answer at a high level without actually respecting the payment breakdown.',
    'cancel_backordered': '**Task:** The customer has a two-item order where the shirt has already shipped and the blender is backordered for more than three weeks. The correct handling is to cancel only the backordered blender and leave the shipped shirt alone, producing the $79 refund for that one item.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to separate what is still cancellable from what is already in motion. Weak agents wipe out the full order, target the shipped item by mistake, or miss that the backordered line is the only valid cancellation path.',
    'cancel_delivered': '**Task:** The customer asks to cancel an order that has already been delivered. At that point cancellation is no longer available, so the right response is to deny the cancellation cleanly and redirect the customer to the return path instead.\n\n**Challenge:** The risk is forcing the request into the wrong workflow. Weak agents try to cancel a completed delivery, improvise a refund anyway, or fail to point the customer toward the proper return process.',
    'cancel_price_match': '**Task:** The customer notices that recently delivered headphones dropped by $50 and wants help. This is a price-match case, not a cancellation case, so the agent should verify the new product price, apply the price-match rule, and refund the $50 difference while leaving the order active.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to choose the right policy surface before acting. Weak agents turn the request into a cancellation or return, skip the product-price verification, or deny the adjustment without checking the price-match rule.',
    'cancel_already_cancelled': '**Task:** The customer asks to cancel an order that is already in a cancelled state. The right handling is simply to explain that no further action is needed and avoid creating any duplicate cancellation or refund activity.\n\n**Challenge:** This is a restraint check. Weak agents try to cancel it again, imply that additional work is required, or speak imprecisely about the order status instead of closing the loop cleanly.',
    'shipping_delivered_not_received': '**Task:** The customer reports a package as delivered but missing on a sub-$500 order with no signature barrier. The correct handling is to treat this as a valid shipping-loss claim and follow the immediate refund path that policy allows.\n\n**Challenge:** The case should stay on the shipping-claim surface rather than drifting into an ordinary return workflow. Weak agents skip the policy check, stall without resolving the claim, or fail to convert the report into the allowed refund outcome.',
    'return_defective_electronics': '**Task:** The customer has a genuinely defective laptop and needs a standard defective-item return. The correct handling is a full refund with no restocking fee and a free return label, keeping the case clearly on the defect path rather than a discretionary return path.\n\n**Challenge:** Classification is the whole issue. Weak agents quietly apply changed-mind logic, add restocking anyway, or forget that a defective-item return should include the free-label treatment.',
    'shipping_high_value_lost': '**Task:** A high-value laptop worth $799 appears to be lost in transit. Because the order is above the $500 threshold, the correct handling is to explain that a three-to-five-business-day investigation is required before any refund or replacement can be issued.\n\n**Challenge:** The policy turns on order value, not on customer urgency. Weak agents issue an immediate refund or reship to be helpful, or mention the problem without making the mandatory investigation step explicit.',
    'shipping_damaged_fragile': '**Task:** A fragile crystal vase arrived damaged in transit. The correct handling is to resolve the damaged-item claim, refund the $85 purchase amount, and include the separate $10 fragile-item goodwill credit that applies to this kind of case.\n\n**Challenge:** More than one compensating action is required here. Weak agents forget the fragile goodwill credit, treat the damage like an ordinary changed-mind return, or add penalties that do not belong on a damage-in-transit claim.',
    'shipping_missing_item': '**Task:** A three-item order was delivered, but the phone case was missing from the box. The right outcome is to resolve the claim for that missing line only and record the $35 refund without disturbing the other delivered items.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to keep the scope narrow and identify the correct missing item. Weak agents process the entire order, refund the wrong product, or blur a one-line missing-item claim into a full return.',
    'shipping_wrong_item': '**Task:** The customer ordered a tablet but received a blender instead. The correct handling is to recognize this as a wrong-item shipment, provide the free return path, and issue the full $599 refund rather than treating it like an ordinary discretionary return.\n\n**Challenge:** Classification matters here. Weak agents charge restocking, fail to confirm the mismatch, or otherwise collapse a fulfillment error into the wrong return policy.',
    'shipping_late_compensation': '**Task:** A Platinum customer received an order four days late. The right resolution is not a return at all, but the late-delivery compensation that results in a $30 refund after applying the Platinum multiplier.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to find the compensation rule and apply the tier logic correctly. Weak agents miss the multiplier, guess at the amount, or treat a service-compensation request as if it required some other order action.',
    'shipping_stuck_in_transit': '**Task:** A package is eight days overdue and now qualifies as likely lost in transit. The correct handling is to use the shipping-loss policy and issue the $67 refund for the affected item without trying to cancel an order that has already shipped.\n\n**Challenge:** The main risk is choosing the wrong workflow. Weak agents never recognize the overdue package as lost, skip the shipping policy check, or reach for cancellation instead of the allowed refund-only shipping resolution.',
    'shipping_signature_conflict': '**Task:** The customer says a package never arrived, but the delivery record shows a signature from Emma Chen on file. Because the signed delivery confirms receipt, the correct outcome is to deny the claim and explain that the signature record controls the decision.\n\n**Challenge:** This is a policy-bound denial even if the customer disputes it. Weak agents refund anyway, ignore the signature evidence, or soften the answer into an unnecessary investigation when the delivery record is already decisive.',
    'warranty_in_warranty_repair': '**Task:** The customer has an in-warranty laptop defect on a high-value item. The correct handling is to process the claim under warranty and route it to repair rather than replacement.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to follow the actual warranty rule instead of improvising a more customer-pleasing outcome. Weak agents jump to replacement or speak vaguely without committing to the repair path.',
    'warranty_expired_recent': "**Task:** The customer is just outside the warranty window, but the policy still allows a fifty-percent discounted repair. The correct handling is to acknowledge that the full warranty has expired while clearly offering the discounted repair option at $199.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to avoid the false choice between full coverage and total denial. Weak agents stop at 'expired,' miss the recent-expiry repair concession, or fail to surface the actual discounted cost.",
    'warranty_extended': "**Task:** The manufacturer's coverage on the tablet has ended, but the customer also has an extended three-year warranty that still covers the issue. The right resolution is to recognize that extended coverage controls here and route the claim to repair.\n\n**Challenge:** The difficult part is checking which warranty actually governs the claim. Weak agents see the expired manufacturer term and deny the case, or never look closely enough to notice that the extended plan keeps the repair path open.",
    'return_outside_window': '**Task:** The customer wants to return headphones twenty days after delivery, which is outside the electronics refund window but still inside the extended store-credit window. The correct handling is to allow the return, keep the restocking deduction, and issue the value as store credit rather than back to the original payment method.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to distinguish between a closed refund window and a still-open store-credit path. Weak agents deny the return entirely or refund to the original payment method even though only store credit is allowed now.',
    'warranty_manufacturer': '**Task:** The customer reports a problem with headphones that are ten months old and still within the twelve-month manufacturer warranty. The correct handling is to recognize that the claim remains covered and route it through the manufacturer-backed repair path.\n\n**Challenge:** This is a straightforward coverage-identification case. Weak agents miss the manufacturer window, steer the customer toward a replacement or repurchase, or talk around the issue without committing to the covered repair resolution.',
    'warranty_recurring_defect': "**Task:** The customer's phone has already been repaired twice, and this third warranty claim triggers the recurring-defect replacement rule. The right outcome is a full replacement, with the agent making clear that the repeat-failure history is what changes the resolution from repair to replacement.\n\n**Challenge:** Claim history is the deciding factor. Weak agents treat this like another routine repair, fail to check the prior claims, or recognize the recurrence without actually moving the case to the required replacement path.",
    'warranty_refurbished': '**Task:** The customer has a refurbished laptop with a shorter ninety-day warranty, and the issue arises around day eighty-four. The correct handling is to recognize that the refurbished-item terms still cover the claim and route it to repair under that shortened warranty.\n\n**Challenge:** The trap is assuming every laptop follows the standard warranty timeline. Weak agents apply the wrong coverage window, deny the claim because the product is refurbished, or never verify which warranty schedule governs the item.',
    'exchange_size_swap': '**Task:** The customer wants a routine same-style size exchange from medium to large. The correct handling is a free like-for-like exchange with no restocking fee and no detour through a return flow.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to recognize the simplest valid path. Weak agents add unnecessary fees, convert the case into a return, or otherwise overcomplicate a basic size swap.',
    'exchange_more_expensive': '**Task:** The customer wants to trade up from standard headphones to the premium model. The correct handling is to complete the exchange and collect the $100 upgrade difference rather than treating the change as a standalone return and repurchase.\n\n**Challenge:** This is mainly about handling the price delta correctly. Weak agents forget to charge the difference, misquote the amount, or reroute the request into a more complicated flow than the exchange policy requires.',
    'exchange_cheaper': '**Task:** The customer wants to downgrade from premium headphones to the lower-priced model. The correct handling is to complete the exchange and return the $200 difference as store credit instead of cash or card refund.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to settle the price difference using the right method. Weak agents refund to the original payment method, invent restocking where none belongs, or miss the store-credit rule that controls downward exchanges.',
    'exchange_out_of_stock': '**Task:** The customer wants to exchange a shirt for running shoes, but the requested replacement is out of stock. The correct handling is to stop short of completing the exchange and instead offer the available alternatives, which are store credit or a waitlist path.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to respond to inventory reality without inventing a successful exchange. Weak agents complete an exchange into unavailable stock, fail to present the alternatives, or get stuck once the preferred replacement cannot be fulfilled.',
    'exchange_no_price_protection': '**Task:** The customer bought headphones at $249, sees that they now cost $199, and tries to use the exchange flow to get the $50 difference back. Because exchange policy does not provide price protection, the correct response is to deny the exchange-based adjustment and suggest the separate return-and-rebuy path if the customer wants to pursue the lower price.\n\n**Challenge:** The request sounds reasonable, but the policy line is clear. Weak agents issue the $50 refund anyway, pretend an exchange can function as a price adjustment, or never check the no-price-protection rule before answering.',
    'exchange_outside_window': '**Task:** The customer wants to exchange a USB hub for headphones thirty-five days after delivery, even though electronics exchanges close after fifteen days. The right outcome is to deny the exchange because the item is outside the applicable window.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to anchor the answer in the correct exchange deadline. Weak agents process the swap anyway, blur the exchange rules with a different return window, or fail to make the timing issue explicit.',
    'compound_return_and_reorder': '**Task:** The customer needs help with defective headphones and wants the matter fully resolved, which requires both the defective-item return and the matching $249 refund. The correct handling is to complete the return path end to end rather than stopping after only part of the state change.\n\n**Challenge:** Multi-step completion is what matters here. Weak agents initiate the return without actually issuing the refund, or misclassify the defect and add penalties to what should be a clean defective-item resolution.',
    'return_promo_recalculation': '**Task:** The customer wants to return the blender from a three-item order that originally used the SAVE15 promotion. The correct handling is to recompute the refund with the promo value redistributed across the remaining order rather than pretending the blender was purchased by itself.\n\n**Challenge:** Return math is the substance of the task. Weak agents ignore the promotion adjustment, quote the wrong refund, or even target the wrong item while trying to unwind the order.',
    'compound_cancel_price_match': "**Task:** The customer wants to cancel pre-shipment headphones and reorder after a $50 price drop. Because the order has not shipped, the correct handling is a normal fee-free cancellation with the full $249 refund, leaving any follow-on repurchase outside the original order flow.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to ground the answer in shipping state rather than in the customer's motivation. Weak agents invent an intercept fee, miss that pre-shipment cancellation is still free, or overcomplicate the case because a price change prompted the request.",
    'compound_return_two_orders': '**Task:** The customer wants help with returns from two separate orders in the same conversation. The correct handling is to keep the orders distinct, process both item returns independently, and preserve the right refund for each order rather than letting the cases bleed together.\n\n**Challenge:** Cross-order bookkeeping is the whole point. Weak agents handle only one order, mix item identities across orders, or lose track of which refund belongs to which purchase.',
    'compound_exchange_plus_credit': "**Task:** The customer wants to exchange $249 headphones for a $349 premium model and also has $150 in store credit available. The correct handling is to recognize the $100 upgrade delta, then apply the existing credit so the customer understands the difference is fully covered rather than charged out of pocket.\n\n**Challenge:** This case depends on combining two valid financial levers in the right order. Weak agents ignore the customer's stored credit, charge the full upgrade amount, or treat the exchange and available credit as unrelated facts.",
    'compound_warranty_then_return': '**Task:** The customer raises two different issues on the same order: a phone with a warranty-covered screen problem and a phone case they simply want to return. The correct handling is to keep those tracks separate, route the phone through warranty, and complete the $35 changed-mind return for the case.\n\n**Challenge:** Mixed-workflow discipline is the core difficulty. Weak agents handle only one issue, confuse which item belongs to which policy path, or collapse the warranty claim and return request into a single muddled action.',
    'compound_return_gift_exchange': '**Task:** The customer wants to turn a gifted blender into store credit and immediately apply that value toward a coffee maker. The correct handling is to use the current gift-return value as store credit and carry it into the replacement purchase flow rather than sending money back to an unavailable payment method.\n\n**Challenge:** Gift-return valuation and refund-method discipline both matter here. Weak agents use the original purchase price, push cash back to a card, or fail to keep the credit inside the gift-return path.',
    'compound_partial_cancel_return': '**Task:** In a two-item order, the shirt has already been delivered and the book has not shipped yet. The correct handling is to return the delivered shirt through the return workflow, cancel only the unshipped book, and record the separate $59 and $14 refunds for those distinct actions.\n\n**Challenge:** The case mixes two valid but different operations. Weak agents try to cancel the delivered item, force both lines through the same workflow, or lose track of which refund belongs to which item.',
    'edge_wrong_order_id': '**Task:** The customer opens with an invalid order ID while asking about a possible return. The correct handling is to recover gracefully by asking for the right order identifier and to avoid taking any return action until the order is clarified.\n\n**Challenge:** Error handling and scope control are the real skills under test. Weak agents crash on lookup, fake confidence about the missing order, or jump into a return flow even though the underlying order is still unknown.',
    'edge_signature_conflict': '**Task:** The customer disputes a laptop delivery, but the order record shows a matching signature from E. Chen. The correct outcome is to rely on the signed-delivery evidence, deny the not-received claim, and explain that the matching signature is why no refund or replacement is available.\n\n**Challenge:** This is an evidence-driven denial. Weak agents ignore the signature, refund the order to be accommodating, or avoid making a firm decision even though the delivery record already resolves the dispute.',
    'edge_all_windows_expired': '**Task:** The customer wants to return electronics sixty-three days after delivery, long past both the fifteen-day return window and the additional fifteen-day store-credit window. The correct handling is to confirm that all eligibility windows have expired and deny the return without creating any state change.\n\n**Challenge:** Timing logic is the full substance of the case. Weak agents skip the eligibility check, offer store credit even though that extension has also expired, or process the return despite the windows being fully closed.',
    'edge_vague_complaint': "**Task:** The customer opens with a vague complaint that the order is 'messed up,' and the agent has to diagnose what actually happened. The correct read is that the customer received a blender when they were supposed to receive a phone case, so the case should be handled as a wrong-item shipment with the $89 refund.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to clarify before acting. Weak agents make assumptions without enough information, process the whole order instead of the actual problematic line, or miss that this is a fulfillment error rather than a generic dissatisfaction return.",
    'return_gift': '**Task:** The customer is returning a gifted pair of headphones without the original receipt. The correct handling is to issue store credit at the current sale value rather than the historical purchase price or any original payment method refund.\n\n**Challenge:** Gift-return valuation and refund-method control both matter here. Weak agents over-refund using the old price, send the value back to an unavailable payment method, or otherwise ignore the rules that make gift returns different.',
    'edge_changes_mind': "**Task:** The customer first asks about exchanging headphones for a premium model, then changes direction and decides they want a full return instead. The correct handling is to follow the customer's final intent, switch cleanly to the changed-mind return path, and issue the $222 refund with the $37 restocking deduction.\n\n**Challenge:** The difficulty is tracking the conversational pivot without clinging to the first request. Weak agents continue down the exchange flow, fail to reset to the return policy, or stumble when the customer reverses course midstream.",
    'challenge_stacked_window': '**Task:** A Gold plus Prime customer is returning electronics thirty-two days after delivery, so the return is valid only because both window extensions stack. The correct handling is to recognize the effective forty-five-day window, allow the return, and keep it on the normal refund path rather than downgrading it to store credit or denial.\n\n**Challenge:** The policy nuance lives in additive eligibility. Weak agents apply only one extension, conclude the window is closed, or miss that stacked perks change the return class entirely.',
    'challenge_fragile_goodwill_separate': '**Task:** A fragile blender arrived damaged in transit, and the correct resolution has two distinct pieces: the return refund and a separate $10 fragile-item goodwill credit. The right handling is to preserve those as separate actions rather than burying everything inside one blended refund.\n\n**Challenge:** Action boundaries are what matter here. Weak agents forget the goodwill credit altogether or merge it into the item refund in a way that loses the actual structure of the remedy.',
    'challenge_remorse_as_defective': "**Task:** The customer calls a tablet defective, but the real issue is cosmetic disappointment rather than a product fault. The correct handling is to reclassify the case as a changed-mind return, apply the normal restocking logic, and avoid handing out the more generous defective-item resolution.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to validate the label instead of copying it. Weak agents accept 'defective' at face value, skip the clarifying step, and over-refund a case that does not actually qualify for defect handling.",
    'challenge_high_value_investigation': '**Task:** A $1,299 laptop is lost in transit, which means the high-value shipping policy requires an investigation before any refund or reship. The correct handling is to explain the three-to-five-business-day investigation requirement and refuse an immediate monetary resolution.\n\n**Challenge:** The policy has to hold even under urgency and premium-customer pressure. Weak agents cave to the demand for an instant refund or replacement and ignore the mandatory high-value investigation step.',
    'challenge_price_match_refund': '**Task:** The customer wants a $50 price-match refund on recently purchased headphones and does not need a cancellation or return. The correct handling is to verify the current price, apply the price-match rule, and issue the refund while leaving the order active.\n\n**Challenge:** Action selection is the whole point. Weak agents turn a price-match request into a return flow, deny the request without checking policy, or compute the difference incorrectly.',
    'challenge_signature_denial': "**Task:** The customer insists a package never arrived, but the delivery record includes a signature from J. Smith. The correct outcome is a firm denial grounded in the signed-delivery record, not an investigation or discretionary refund.\n\n**Challenge:** Pressure handling matters here because the evidence is already conclusive. Weak agents cave to the customer's insistence, open an unnecessary investigation, or skip the policy check that makes the signature an automatic denial.",
    'challenge_false_damage_claim': "**Task:** The customer describes a problem as shipping damage, but the order record shows a normal delivery and the situation does not support a damaged-in-transit classification. The correct handling is to reframe the request as a changed-mind return instead of granting the more generous damage-based path.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to validate the classification rather than accept the customer's label. Weak agents grant a damaged-shipment resolution without checking the shipping record, or use the wrong rationale even if the final number happens to look plausible.",
    'challenge_store_credit_only_pushback': '**Task:** A Platinum customer is outside the full-refund window but still inside the store-credit window for a headphones return. The correct handling is to allow the return, keep the refund as store credit only, and hold that line even when the customer pushes for the original payment method instead.\n\n**Challenge:** This is a policy-discipline case under social pressure. Weak agents over-index on the Platinum tier, deny the return entirely, or cave and invent a card refund that the timing rules no longer allow.',
    'challenge_damaged_plus_wrong': '**Task:** The customer has two legitimate fulfillment problems at once: a fragile scale that arrived damaged and a shirt that is the wrong item. The correct handling is to resolve both lines, refund the damaged scale and the wrong-item shirt separately, and also include the extra $10 fragile-item goodwill credit tied to the damaged scale.\n\n**Challenge:** This case rewards complete bookkeeping across multiple issue types. Weak agents resolve only one item, forget the fragile goodwill credit, or muddle the two problems into one incomplete action.',
    'return_wrong_item': "**Task:** The customer ordered a laptop but received a blender instead. That makes this a wrong-item shipment case, so the correct handling is the free return path with the full $1,299 refund rather than any discretionary-return logic.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to preserve the fulfillment-error classification all the way through resolution. Weak agents add restocking, forget the free-label path, or otherwise treat a seller mistake as if it were buyer's remorse.",
    'challenge_low_value_lost_immediate': '**Task:** A low-value $89 blender is lost in transit. Because the claim is under the $500 threshold, the correct handling is to offer an immediate refund or reship without imposing any investigation delay.\n\n**Challenge:** The temptation is to overgeneralize from the high-value shipping rule. Weak agents start a three-to-five-day investigation anyway, tell the customer to wait when immediate resolution is allowed, or deny relief altogether.',
    'challenge_standard_1day_pushback': "**Task:** A Standard customer experienced a one-day delay with two issues, which qualifies for only $5 in compensation. The correct handling is to issue that amount and hold the line even when the customer pushes aggressively for something much larger.\n\n**Challenge:** The case is really about resisting pressure without inventing policy exceptions. Weak agents inflate the credit to appease the customer, add goodwill that is not warranted, or let the customer's framing override the actual compensation rule.",
    'challenge_exchange_oos_pivot': '**Task:** The customer asks for an exchange, but the desired replacement is out of stock and ultimately chooses a refund instead. The correct handling is to explain the out-of-stock constraint, offer the available alternatives, and then complete the changed-mind return path with the $222 refund minus the $37 restocking fee once the customer pivots.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to adapt when the first path becomes unavailable. Weak agents keep trying to force the exchange, fail to offer a refund alternative, or stall after discovering the replacement cannot be fulfilled.',
    'challenge_bulk_clawback': '**Task:** The customer is returning headphones and a shirt from a four-item order that originally qualified for a bulk discount. Once those two items come out, the order drops below the bulk threshold, so the correct handling is to process both returns and account for the $10 clawback that now applies.\n\n**Challenge:** The refund math has to reflect the changed order composition. Weak agents miss the bulk clawback entirely, mention it vaguely without actually applying it, or deduct the wrong amount from the combined return.',
    'challenge_seasonal_valid': '**Task:** The order was placed in November and the customer is returning it on January 15, after the normal refund and store-credit windows but still inside the seasonal extension that runs through January 31. The correct handling is to recognize that the seasonal policy keeps the return fully valid and process the normal refund.\n\n**Challenge:** The key is noticing that the special calendar rule overrides the expired standard windows. Weak agents deny the return based on the usual deadline, downgrade it to store credit, or never check the seasonal policy at all.',
    'challenge_defective_plus_clawback': '**Task:** The customer is returning a defective tablet from a three-item bulk-discounted order. The defective item should still receive its full refund treatment, but the order also falls below the bulk threshold afterward, so the separate $10 bulk clawback on the remaining order has to be recognized.\n\n**Challenge:** Two policies have to coexist without contaminating each other. Weak agents subtract promo value from the defective-item refund, forget the downstream bulk clawback, or never explain that the clawback follows from the changed qualifying item count.',
    'challenge_seasonal_electronics': '**Task:** The customer wants to return a USB hub in early January after the normal electronics window has closed, but the order qualifies for the seasonal extension through January 31. The correct handling is to recognize that the seasonal rule revives eligibility and process the changed-mind return with the normal restocking logic.\n\n**Challenge:** This case breaks agents that treat the electronics deadline as absolute. Weak agents stop at the fifteen-day rule, deny the return outright, or offer store credit when a full valid return is still available under the seasonal policy.',
    'challenge_seasonal_plus_bulk_clawback': '**Task:** A November order with four items and a discount code is still returnable in January only because the seasonal extension applies. The correct handling is to process both requested returns and also recognize that removing two of the four items drops the order below the bulk threshold, triggering the $10 clawback.\n\n**Challenge:** This is a layered policy case, not a single-rule lookup. Weak agents miss the seasonal extension and deny the return, process the returns without the bulk adjustment, or complete only one of the two lines.',
    'challenge_seasonal_plus_shipping_clawback': '**Task:** A Standard customer is returning a blender from a November order in January, so the return is valid only because of the seasonal extension. Once the blender is removed, the remaining order drops below the free-shipping threshold, which means the correct handling also includes the $8 shipping clawback.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to hold two separate policy ideas at once: seasonal eligibility and free-shipping reversal. Weak agents notice one but not the other, deny the return using the normal window, or refund the blender without the required shipping adjustment.',
    'challenge_silver_restock_plus_shipping': '**Task:** A Silver customer is returning a $599 tablet from a free-shipping order. The correct handling is to process the changed-mind return, keep the base $89 restocking deduction, issue the separate $22 Silver restocking-discount credit, and also apply the $10 shipping clawback because the remaining order falls below the free-shipping threshold.\n\n**Challenge:** Several financial adjustments stack here, but they do not collapse into one generic number. Weak agents charge the full restocking fee without the Silver credit, miss the shipping clawback, or surface only one of the two policy adjustments.',
    'return_restocking_waived': "**Task:** A Platinum customer wants to return opened headphones for changed mind. The correct handling is to process the return on the normal refund path while waiving the electronics restocking fee because Platinum status overrides that deduction.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to notice that membership changes the economics without changing the rest of the workflow. Weak agents charge the ordinary restocking fee anyway or fail to tie the waiver back to the customer's tier.",
    'challenge_free_shipping_clawback': '**Task:** A Standard customer returns a blender from a two-item order that originally qualified for free shipping at $148. Once the blender is removed, the order drops below the $100 threshold, so the correct handling is to deduct the $8 free-shipping clawback and return $81 rather than the full item price.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to recalculate based on the remaining order, not just the returned item. Weak agents refund the full $89, never check the free-shipping policy, or understand the clawback conceptually without applying it to the final amount.',
    'challenge_repeat_category_return': '**Task:** A Gold customer is returning two clothing items from the same order. The first shirt follows the ordinary path, but the second same-category return carries the extra $5 repeat surcharge, so the correct handling is to refund the first at $59 and the second at $54.\n\n**Challenge:** The hard part is noticing that the second line is not symmetric with the first. Weak agents refund both items identically, miss the repeat-return rule, or fail to tie the surcharge specifically to the later clothing return.',
    'challenge_bulk_plus_shipping_clawback': '**Task:** A Standard customer is returning a blender and a shirt from a four-item order that had both a bulk discount and free shipping. Once those two items are removed, the order loses both benefits, so the correct handling is to process both returns while applying the $10 bulk clawback and the $8 shipping clawback.\n\n**Challenge:** This is a double-clawback case where incomplete math is the most common failure. Weak agents catch only one adjustment, refund both items as if the original perks still applied, or miss that the post-return order state drives both deductions.',
    'challenge_gold_restocking_discount': '**Task:** A Gold customer is returning a laptop with a substantial restocking fee, but Gold status entitles them to a separate fifty-percent restocking-discount credit. The correct handling is to process the return, keep the base restocking deduction, and then issue the $97 credit through the proper refund path.\n\n**Challenge:** This is multi-step financial handling rather than a single net-number answer. Weak agents forget the Gold credit entirely, waive the restocking fee outright, or never issue the required second credit.',
    'challenge_promo_bulk_repeat': '**Task:** A Standard customer is returning two clothing items from a four-item order that used the SPRING20 promotion and also qualified for the bulk threshold. The correct handling is to process both returns, preserve the promo-adjusted item values, apply the $10 bulk clawback once the order drops from four items to two, and add the $5 repeat surcharge to the second clothing return.\n\n**Challenge:** The case bundles promo math, order-level clawback, and category-level surcharge into one resolution. Weak agents miss one of the adjustments, treat the two shirts as identical, or stop after processing only one return.',
    'challenge_gold_restock_on_promo': '**Task:** A Gold customer is returning headphones from a SAVE10 promo order. The correct handling is to account for the promo redistribution and the normal $37 restocking deduction, then issue the separate $18 Gold restocking-discount credit rather than waiving the fee outright.\n\n**Challenge:** The subtlety is that Gold changes the economics without erasing the base fee. Weak agents forget the Gold credit, eliminate the restocking charge entirely as if the customer were Platinum, or lose the promo adjustment while focusing on the membership discount.',
    'challenge_plat_no_restock_but_shipping': '**Task:** A Platinum customer is returning a laptop, so the restocking fee is waived, but the order also loses free shipping once the return drops the remaining subtotal below the threshold. The correct handling is to honor the Platinum restocking waiver while still applying the separate $12 shipping clawback, producing the $491 refund.\n\n**Challenge:** The customer benefit is narrower than it first appears. Weak agents assume Platinum means no deductions of any kind, miss the free-shipping reversal, or let the waived restocking fee obscure the need for a separate shipping adjustment.',
    'challenge_seasonal_gold_restocking': '**Task:** A Gold plus Prime customer is returning headphones in January, and the return is valid because the seasonal extension keeps the window open. The correct handling is to process the return, keep the normal restocking deduction in place, and then issue the separate $18 Gold restocking-discount credit.\n\n**Challenge:** The case combines eligibility and post-eligibility math. Weak agents deny the return because they miss the seasonal rule, process it without the Gold credit, or waive the fee outright instead of applying the proper Gold discount structure.',
    'challenge_defective_shipping_clawback': "**Task:** A Standard customer is returning a defective blender from a free-shipping order. The defect means there is no restocking fee and the item itself stays on the full defective-return path, but the order still drops below the free-shipping threshold afterward, so the shipping clawback remains part of the overall resolution.\n\n**Challenge:** The trap is assuming 'defective' wipes away every downstream consequence. Weak agents treat the case as globally deduction-free and never account for the separate order-level shipping effect.",
    'challenge_user_error_as_defective': "**Task:** The customer says the headphones 'don't work,' but the details reveal a Bluetooth pairing problem rather than a product defect. The correct handling is to recognize this as user error, reframe the case as a changed-mind return, and apply the normal $37 restocking logic instead of granting a defect-based exception.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to diagnose the substance of the complaint instead of copying the customer's label. Weak agents accept 'defective' at face value, skip the clarifying step, or hand out a no-fee resolution for what is really not a defect.",
    'return_high_value': '**Task:** The customer wants to return a high-value laptop under Platinum status. The correct handling is a standard changed-mind return with the Platinum restocking waiver honored, so the item is returned cleanly without the usual electronics deduction.\n\n**Challenge:** Tier-aware return handling is the main issue. Weak agents charge restocking anyway or fail to recognize that the membership waiver still governs even on an expensive item.',
    'challenge_two_electronics_gold': '**Task:** A Gold customer is returning two electronics items, and each line has its own restocking math while the second one also triggers the repeat same-category surcharge. The correct handling is to apply the Gold restocking-discount credit to both items and add the $5 repeat surcharge to the USB hub as the second electronics return.\n\n**Challenge:** This case rewards item-level accounting rather than order-level averaging. Weak agents miss one of the Gold credits, forget the repeat surcharge on the second line, or resolve only one of the two electronics returns.',
    'challenge_low_value_return_shipping': '**Task:** A Standard customer is returning a $35 phone case from an order whose total value stays below $50. The correct handling is to apply the low-value return-shipping fee and refund $27 rather than the full item price.\n\n**Challenge:** The case looks small, but the threshold rule still matters. Weak agents refund the full $35, ignore the low-value return-shipping policy, or talk about the fee without actually reflecting it in the refund amount.',
    'challenge_low_value_electronics_silver': '**Task:** A Silver customer is returning a $45 USB hub from a low-value order. The correct handling is to combine the normal $6 electronics restocking fee, the separate $1 Silver restocking-discount credit, and the $8 low-value return-shipping fee to reach the proper $32 refund.\n\n**Challenge:** Three modest adjustments stack here, which makes partial reasoning easy to miss. Weak agents forget the Silver credit, skip the return-shipping fee, or apply only one of the policies while overlooking the rest.',
    'challenge_missing_single_item_claim': "**Task:** The customer says the blender is missing from the package, but the order had only one item and tracking shows delivery, so this is really a delivered-not-received shipping claim rather than a return. The correct handling is to treat it as a shipping-loss path and offer the allowed refund or reship choice without inventing a return flow.\n\n**Challenge:** Issue-type diagnosis is the whole difficulty. Weak agents follow the customer's wording too literally, create a nonsense return for an item that was never in hand, or miss the shipping-claim policy entirely.",
    'challenge_seasonal_return_shipping': '**Task:** A Standard customer is returning a $35 phone case in January from a November order. The seasonal extension keeps the return eligible, but the order still falls under the low-value threshold, so the correct handling also includes the $8 return-shipping fee.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to resolve both eligibility and pricing. Weak agents deny the return because they miss the seasonal extension, allow it but forget the return-shipping charge, or treat the January timing as irrelevant in both directions.',
    'challenge_seasonal_repeat_clothing': '**Task:** A Standard customer is returning a shirt and a pair of shoes from a November order in January. The seasonal extension makes both returns valid, and because the shoes are the second clothing-category return, the correct handling also includes the $5 repeat surcharge on that second line.\n\n**Challenge:** This is a two-layer case. Weak agents miss the seasonal rule, forget that the later clothing item is not refunded on the same terms as the first, or process only one of the two returns.',
    'challenge_seasonal_bulk_shipping_triple': '**Task:** A November four-item order is being partially returned in January, so the seasonal extension is what keeps the request valid. Once the shirt and shoes come out, the order also loses both its bulk-discount qualification and its free-shipping qualification, so the correct handling includes the $10 bulk clawback and the $8 shipping clawback on top of the two returns.\n\n**Challenge:** This is a true multi-policy reconciliation case. Weak agents stop at eligibility, apply only one clawback, or refund the items as though the original order perks still survive the return.',
    'challenge_social_gold_demands_plat_waiver': '**Task:** A Gold customer is returning headphones and demands the full restocking waiver that only Platinum customers receive. The correct handling is to hold the policy line, keep the standard $37 restocking deduction in place, and issue only the Gold-level fifty-percent restocking-discount credit.\n\n**Challenge:** Customer pressure is the main threat here. Weak agents invent an exception, upgrade the customer to a Platinum outcome they did not earn, or otherwise confuse the Gold discount with the separate Platinum waiver.',
    'challenge_social_return_shipping_fee': '**Task:** A Standard customer is returning a $24 book from a low-value order and is upset that the $8 return-shipping fee takes a large bite out of the refund. The correct handling is still to apply the fee and return $16 rather than waiving it under pressure.\n\n**Challenge:** The case is about staying policy-accurate when the fee feels emotionally disproportionate. Weak agents waive the shipping charge to appease the customer, partially discount it without support, or claim a free-return exception that does not exist.',
    'challenge_gold_restock_shipping_clawback': '**Task:** A Gold customer is returning a laptop from a free-shipping order. The correct handling is to keep the $74 base restocking deduction, issue the separate $37 Gold restocking-discount credit, and also apply the $10 shipping clawback because the order no longer qualifies for free shipping after the return.\n\n**Challenge:** Multiple adjustments apply, but they should not be flattened into a single vague refund story. Weak agents miss the Gold credit, forget the shipping clawback, or handle one correctly while dropping the other.',
    'return_gold_restocking': "**Task:** A Gold customer is returning opened electronics for changed mind. The correct handling is to process the return with the normal electronics restocking fee still in place, because only Platinum customers receive the full restocking waiver.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to distinguish between Gold and Platinum benefits instead of treating all higher tiers the same. Weak agents waive the fee entirely or fail to check the customer's tier before quoting the outcome.",
    'challenge_return_shipping_plus_repeat': '**Task:** A Standard customer is returning two phone cases from a $44 order. The first return triggers the $8 low-value return-shipping fee, and the second same-category return also carries the $5 repeat surcharge, so the two lines must be settled differently.\n\n**Challenge:** The refunds are intentionally asymmetric even though the items match. Weak agents apply the shipping fee without the repeat surcharge, treat both cases identically, or fail to sequence the second same-category adjustment correctly.',
    'challenge_wear_as_not_described': "**Task:** The customer claims a shirt was not as described, but also reveals that it has already been worn and washed, which points away from a genuine listing mismatch and toward buyer's remorse. The correct handling is to classify the case as a changed-mind return rather than a product-fault claim.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to probe beyond the customer's label and use the fuller context. Weak agents accept 'not as described' at face value, skip the usage clarification, or grant a fault-based resolution that the underlying facts do not support.",
    'challenge_seasonal_restock_shipping_triple': '**Task:** A Silver customer is returning headphones in January from a December order, so the seasonal extension is what makes the return possible. The correct handling is to process the return, issue the separate $9 Silver restocking-discount credit against the normal electronics fee, and also apply the $8 shipping clawback tied to the remaining order.\n\n**Challenge:** This case combines timing, membership, and order-threshold effects. Weak agents deny the return because they miss the seasonal rule, notice the return but miss the Silver credit, or forget the shipping clawback once the other adjustments are in view.',
    'challenge_seasonal_repeat_shipping': '**Task:** A free-shipping November order is being partially returned in January, so the seasonal extension keeps the return alive. Because the customer is returning two clothing items, the second one carries the $5 repeat surcharge, and because the remaining order drops below the shipping threshold, the correct handling also includes the $8 shipping clawback.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to keep three moving parts straight at once. Weak agents deny the January return, remember the seasonal rule but miss one of the later financial adjustments, or flatten the two clothing lines into identical refunds.',
    'challenge_promo_shipping_restock_gold': '**Task:** A Gold customer is returning headphones from a promo order that also originally qualified for free shipping. The correct handling is to account for promo redistribution, keep the normal $37 restocking deduction, issue the separate $18 Gold restocking-discount credit, and apply the $8 shipping clawback because the return changes the remaining order economics.\n\n**Challenge:** This is stacked refund math where each adjustment comes from a different rule. Weak agents miss the Gold credit, forget the shipping clawback, or focus on the membership discount while dropping the promo-aware refund calculation.',
    'challenge_gold_repeat_restock_shipping': '**Task:** A Gold customer is returning both headphones and a USB hub from a free-shipping order. The correct handling is to apply the Gold restocking-discount credit to both electronics lines, add the $5 repeat same-category surcharge to the second item, and also account for the $10 shipping clawback caused by the reduced remaining order.\n\n**Challenge:** The main risk is incomplete item-by-item accounting. Weak agents remember only one of the Gold credits, miss the repeat surcharge, or ignore the shipping clawback once the return logic becomes more complex.',
    'challenge_seasonal_low_value_silver_electronics': '**Task:** A Silver customer is returning a USB hub in January from a December order, so the seasonal extension keeps the request eligible. The correct handling is to apply the normal $6 electronics restocking fee, issue the separate $1 Silver restocking-discount credit, and also include the $8 low-value return-shipping fee.\n\n**Challenge:** This task hinges on combining one timing rule with two small financial adjustments. Weak agents deny the return based on the normal electronics window, or process it while missing either the Silver credit or the return-shipping fee.',
    'challenge_triple_same_category_return': '**Task:** The customer is returning three clothing items from a four-item order. The first item follows the ordinary path, but both the second and third same-category returns carry the extra $5 repeat surcharge, so the correct handling applies that surcharge twice across the later two lines.\n\n**Challenge:** The agent has to track category repetition across more than one follow-on item. Weak agents apply the surcharge only once, forget it entirely, or stop after returning only part of the requested set.',
    'challenge_triple_action': '**Task:** A fragile kitchen scale arrived damaged and four days late, so the correct resolution has three distinct parts: the return refund, the late-delivery compensation, and the fragile-item goodwill credit. The right handling is to complete all three pieces without collapsing them into one generic write.\n\n**Challenge:** This case asks the agent to carry a compound resolution across multiple policy surfaces. Weak agents handle only the return, forget the goodwill credit, or merge the compensations into one incorrect action.',
    'challenge_gold_7day_all_parts': "**Task:** A Gold customer had an order arrive seven days late with three separate service issues, so the correct resolution bundles three components: $22 in delay compensation after Gold's multiplier and integer truncation, a $12 shipping refund, and a $25 goodwill credit, for a total of $59.\n\n**Challenge:** The arithmetic is easy to mangle because not every component scales the same way. Weak agents round the delay credit to $22.50, multiply the goodwill or shipping refund incorrectly, or otherwise lose the exact structure of the three-part compensation.",
}
